WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.560
Hi everyone. I'm Cynthia, a PhD candidate from Monash University all the way in Australia,

00:00:07.200 --> 00:00:10.400
a data scientist, podcast host, and Quarto enthusiast.

00:00:11.280 --> 00:00:14.960
So very clearly I am a serial hat collector and plate juggler.

00:00:16.959 --> 00:00:21.600
Unsurprisingly, things can get kind of chaotic. Too many ideas up here, too little time.

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:26.799
So naturally, I need strategies and tools to wrangle the chaos.

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:32.959
Before Quarto, this mostly looked like every knowledge management solution under the sun.

00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:42.560
This includes sticky notes, notebooks that I did not finish, and a lot, though not all,

00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:44.560
of the productivity apps out there on offer.

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:52.080
Now I do most of my note-taking in Quarto, maybe 80, 90%. I still use sticky notes.

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:57.360
And this talk is going to be how I use Quarto to kind of get started with simple,

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:02.480
powerful, and fun note-taking or knowledge management.

00:01:04.400 --> 00:01:10.400
So even though this talk is Quarto for Knowledge Management, it's really Quarto for Managing My Brain.

00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:16.160
So I'm going to take you on a bit of a tour on some of the websites, computations,

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:21.680
some of the websites, computations, and extensions of Quarto that I've used to

00:01:21.680 --> 00:01:26.400
organize my research work and research collaborations.

00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:33.599
So first up, Quarto websites provide structure and variety for very minimal effort.

00:01:35.279 --> 00:01:40.400
What you see on screen here is actually an example website that I used

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:44.559
to apply for this talk because I didn't want to share my private secrets.

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:50.879
So really, all you need to get started is a Quarto website.

00:01:50.879 --> 00:01:57.440
It's an incredibly stable format, very easy to debug. I don't know much HTML or CSS,

00:01:57.440 --> 00:02:02.320
but Quarto websites allow me to get started with a couple of Quarto documents,

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:11.440
a bit of YAML, and there I have on screen a collection of notes on PositConf 2023 talks

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:13.679
that I used to inspire me for this talk.

00:02:16.240 --> 00:02:22.320
With a little bit more YAML, you can set up listings, table of contents,

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:25.520
all of these cool things that help you navigate your notes.

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:33.440
And so on screen here, you can see that I think I watched like four or five talks in order to

00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:36.800
prepare my application, and I wrote some notes on each of these,

00:02:36.800 --> 00:02:38.559
and then I put them all together in a listing.

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:45.279
The other really cool thing about Quarto is that it offers visual variety pretty much

00:02:45.279 --> 00:02:52.000
out of the box with just one line of code or one change to your code, which is this theme option.

00:02:53.199 --> 00:02:58.880
A lot of other knowledge management tools like Notion or Obsidian are actually visually very

00:02:58.880 --> 00:03:01.919
similar, so every single note you ever make will look the same.

00:03:02.559 --> 00:03:06.559
That's nice, but I like a little bit of variety, and my brain really craves it,

00:03:06.559 --> 00:03:13.520
so being able to just change up the look of my different notes really helps me switch contexts.

00:03:14.720 --> 00:03:19.839
And so switching contexts a little bit, this is probably the application of Quarto websites

00:03:19.839 --> 00:03:25.119
that I'm most excited about. It is a Quarto website that contains pretty much everything

00:03:25.119 --> 00:03:32.399
I've done over the last three years in my PhD. I can kind of search it for almost everything,

00:03:32.639 --> 00:03:38.320
I can kind of search it for almost everything, so meetings that I've taken with my supervisors,

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:42.559
publication drafts or submissions that I've made.

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:50.080
On screen right here is my final progress review report, and so everything that I've ever made

00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:55.440
is here, and hopefully, if everything goes smoothly, when I submit early next year,

00:03:55.440 --> 00:04:01.360
this will be kind of the artifact that I get from going through this entire PhD process.

00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:07.759
The other kind of really cool thing that I've played around with in Quarto, and you'll see that

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:16.320
especially in here, I have used a number of different formats to keep track of definitions.

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:22.160
So I'm an interdisciplinary researcher, and what this basically means is that I have my fingers in

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:27.279
a lot of different disciplines, and one kind of interesting and cool thing about humans,

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:32.000
you know, researching a particular area is you come up with words to describe things,

00:04:32.079 --> 00:04:39.920
but different people in different areas use the same words for different ideas, or they use

00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:46.559
different words for the same idea. So one thing that I've done when I'm kind of researching or

00:04:46.559 --> 00:04:51.760
reading into a new field, I try to keep track of the definitions that I come across, and this is

00:04:51.760 --> 00:04:58.640
really helpful when I then go to write up a paper to be able to reference these different definitions.

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:04.640
I actually found out earlier in this conference another really cool way of doing definitions

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:10.640
that uses some Lua filter magic, which I'm going to try out, but you can actually see here that

00:05:10.640 --> 00:05:18.320
I've got listings as well as just like definitions dumped in the table and other things. So this is

00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:29.600
very much my internal inbox of things that are helpful for me, and the great thing about Quoto

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:35.279
is that it's okay that it's a bit messy. It's okay that I don't know exactly how I want all

00:05:35.279 --> 00:05:40.799
my notes structured, because having everything in plain text means reorganizing is super simple.

00:05:41.519 --> 00:05:49.200
If I have a particular set of notes that actually I want to put into, say, a presentation or I want

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:55.760
to share with my supervisors, I can just take those documents out, set up a new YAML configuration,

00:05:55.760 --> 00:06:01.920
and then I've got a whole other Quoto project that I can share with other people. I can rearrange

00:06:01.920 --> 00:06:09.119
things into folders and use the kind of auto table of contents generation to populate the website.

00:06:09.119 --> 00:06:12.799
There's heaps of cool things that are all powered by the magic of Quoto

00:06:12.799 --> 00:06:16.640
and plain text. Oh, and version control, which is very, very important.

00:06:18.239 --> 00:06:23.040
So next up, I want to talk a little bit about how Quoto computations and extensions

00:06:23.040 --> 00:06:28.160
supercharge my coding skills to turn my kind of web design dreams into reality.

00:06:29.440 --> 00:06:34.720
So you might remember I have many hats, but web developer is not one of them.

00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:39.279
Not for lack of interest, mostly out of responsibility for looking after my time.

00:06:40.399 --> 00:06:50.079
But I have built, with the help of Quoto, these three interactive web page things

00:06:50.079 --> 00:06:59.119
that I'm going to talk to you a little bit about. So first up, in maybe March of this year,

00:06:59.119 --> 00:07:05.839
I was actually planning a rather long research trip. I'm very fortunate to have been able to

00:07:05.839 --> 00:07:11.040
attend USAR prior to this conference, and I'll be spending a couple of months here in North America.

00:07:11.839 --> 00:07:17.839
But the actual process of planning and booking this trip, because I am a lowly PhD student with

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:24.399
no one else to book flights or hotels for me, meant that I had to do a lot of planning.

00:07:24.399 --> 00:07:31.839
And so one way to kind of engage myself in this somewhat tedious task was, I thought to myself,

00:07:31.839 --> 00:07:37.600
well, why don't I make a calendar where I can put in all the dates where I have to be somewhere?

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:44.320
So conferences or research visits. I want a calendar where I can see all of those dates and

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:49.359
then figure out, you know, what are the dates I still have to fill? Where maybe could I fit in,

00:07:49.359 --> 00:07:55.679
you know, a little bit of leisure travel? And so this is my sketch of what I wanted this calendar

00:07:55.679 --> 00:08:02.160
to look like. Again, I don't have any web design or web development skills, but I do know how to

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:12.320
code in R and use Quoto. So here on screen is the code that I came up with using a little bit of

00:08:12.399 --> 00:08:20.959
dplyr magic, a list of the events that I had to go to, and some ggplot code, which is now wrapped

00:08:20.959 --> 00:08:29.600
up in a separate package called ggtilecal. And that couple of lines of code, I mean, it's a

00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:33.679
few more than a couple, took me a little while to build, but it was a really fun thing to do,

00:08:34.559 --> 00:08:43.919
helped me create this, which is just an interactive calendar powered pretty much

00:08:43.919 --> 00:08:53.520
exclusively with ggplot and dplyr with a couple of other extensions. And yes, it took a bit of time,

00:08:53.520 --> 00:09:01.039
but it also engaged me in the task of planning for this trip. Next up, one thing I'm really

00:09:01.039 --> 00:09:07.280
passionate about is using graphics to communicate research. I think it's a really important and

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:14.960
effective way to communicate complex ideas. And the annoying thing about that, though,

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:21.440
is I often sketch these images and then I'm looking through past presentations or going

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:27.039
through different folders to try and find the graphics that I've made maybe three or six months

00:09:27.039 --> 00:09:34.239
ago. And so I thought to myself, well, what if I just put all of these images into a single GitHub

00:09:34.239 --> 00:09:40.239
repository, and wouldn't it be cool if I could just have the README show me every image that

00:09:40.239 --> 00:09:46.559
I've ever made and maybe also print the file name so that when I'm including this image, say, in a

00:09:46.559 --> 00:09:53.119
set of Quoto slides or in my next paper, I know where to find that file and what it's called.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:10:00.799
So how did I do that? Really handily with just a little bit of glue. So with glue, you can

00:10:00.799 --> 00:10:08.719
basically construct strings and using the output as is option in Quoto, you can basically write

00:10:08.719 --> 00:10:17.919
markdown using our code. And so right here, this piece of code looks into a file directory,

00:10:18.799 --> 00:10:26.479
looks for all of the images, and then basically constructs a markdown image link

00:10:26.479 --> 00:10:32.719
for each one of these images, and then also prints the name of those images for me.

00:10:35.200 --> 00:10:41.119
Okay. So what does this look like? This is this GitHub repository,

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:47.359
kind of collection of images that I've made throughout my PhD research process,

00:10:47.359 --> 00:10:52.960
a hex sticker for my package as well, some plots that I've made, a poster that I've made,

00:10:52.960 --> 00:10:57.200
everything that I've made to do with my first two research projects,

00:10:57.200 --> 00:11:02.320
all come down to a little line of code that I showed you on the previous page.

00:11:02.880 --> 00:11:12.080
Okay. Last but not least, I really love a, like, tell by now to draw. Like, I love kind of visual,

00:11:12.080 --> 00:11:17.280
making visual things. And so one thing I've always wanted to do is have a kind of interactive

00:11:17.280 --> 00:11:23.359
image gallery tile type thing of some of the things that I've made and drawn. But I don't

00:11:23.359 --> 00:11:27.119
have any JavaScript skills. Like, we established that before. I'm not a web developer.

00:11:27.119 --> 00:11:35.039
However, someone has made a masonry extension and Lightbox, which both of these are JavaScript

00:11:35.039 --> 00:11:43.760
libraries, have been incorporated into Quoto. So as of Quoto 1.4, you can use Lightbox kind of

00:11:43.760 --> 00:11:49.840
out of the box with Quoto. And then someone's made an experimental but stable enough for me

00:11:49.919 --> 00:11:55.599
Quoto extension to use masonry. And so this is kind of the little bit of code that I had to write

00:11:56.320 --> 00:12:04.080
to generate this. And so these are sketches that I made in the last couple of months while I was

00:12:04.080 --> 00:12:11.599
traveling in Europe. And it looks exactly, well, not exactly, 90% to the way of how I imagined it

00:12:11.599 --> 00:12:16.880
in my head. So I'm going to show you a little bit of what I mean by that. So I'm going to start

00:12:17.840 --> 00:12:23.760
to the way of how I imagined it in my brain. And this would have taken me, well, never. I would

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:27.919
never have done it without Quoto because I was not going to learn JavaScript.

00:12:30.080 --> 00:12:34.400
So I cheated a little on that last one in that, you know, I was talking to you about

00:12:34.400 --> 00:12:39.280
internal note taking. That last one's actually on my blog. But leads me to my last point,

00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:44.159
which is that private experiments really have leveled up my Quoto skills and provided a very

00:12:44.159 --> 00:12:50.239
safe playground to kind of just learn new Quoto things that have then led me to produce things

00:12:50.239 --> 00:12:55.520
like this, which is a multi-format CV. I think this is maybe the most visited blog post

00:12:56.159 --> 00:13:03.039
on my website. So when this feature where you could do kind of multi-format publishing came

00:13:03.039 --> 00:13:09.679
out in Quoto, I played around with it internally in my PhD log and then created this multi-format

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:17.840
CV where I have the same Quoto document rendering to both a webpage on my website as well as PDF

00:13:17.840 --> 00:13:26.159
output. Some other things that I've made include these research notes, which I share with

00:13:26.159 --> 00:13:32.080
collaborators. And this is actually built upon the manuscripts Quoto project type, which is

00:13:32.719 --> 00:13:39.359
sort of like the website format, but like on steroids for scientific publishing. It's got a

00:13:39.599 --> 00:13:46.400
lot of really cool features and you can kind of connect it up to a journal template. But right

00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:54.159
here, I was working with some collaborators around building a kind of data tidying tool.

00:13:54.159 --> 00:14:01.039
And I just wanted to illustrate kind of which cells we were kind of interested in having the

00:14:01.039 --> 00:14:06.880
user interact with. And so I used the package emphatic here to kind of highlight a couple of

00:14:06.880 --> 00:14:12.559
lines of code. But the kind of really nice thing is this is all code that could then get reused to

00:14:12.559 --> 00:14:21.359
generate graphics for say the paper. And it's all version controlled and I didn't need to develop

00:14:21.359 --> 00:14:27.599
any new skills after I'd kind of played around with Quoto in my own private repository.

00:14:29.760 --> 00:14:35.119
Okay. And then the last thing is that I've written a bunch of templates and blog posts,

00:14:35.119 --> 00:14:41.359
which really helped me get to my first Posit Conference. And so I've taken some of the things

00:14:41.359 --> 00:14:47.919
that I've kind of played around with and experimented with in my private kind of internal

00:14:47.919 --> 00:14:57.280
wiki and turned them into tutorials. And part of that is how I think I ended up here.

00:14:58.880 --> 00:15:04.479
Or at least this is, you know, I think part of the giving back to community as well.

00:15:06.080 --> 00:15:12.239
So hopefully I've convinced you that Quoto for knowledge management can be simple, powerful,

00:15:12.239 --> 00:15:17.520
and fun. And if you're not yet convinced, I'm going to show you one last really cool trick that

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:23.840
actually convinced me initially to swap over from Notion that I was using before and go kind of all

00:15:23.840 --> 00:15:32.400
in on using Quoto to take pretty much all of my notes. And that is visual mode. So you can tell

00:15:32.559 --> 00:15:39.200
now I really like pictures. And so yes, Quoto is amazing because of plain text, but I really like

00:15:39.200 --> 00:15:45.520
being able to drag and drop pictures or copy and paste pictures. And so one thing you can do in

00:15:45.520 --> 00:15:51.280
visual mode is that there is, I don't know how it works behind the scenes, but this is actually

00:15:51.280 --> 00:15:57.599
Positron. The same thing works in RStudio and in VS Code. But if you switch your document to visual

00:15:57.599 --> 00:16:04.000
mode, you can just copy and paste or drag in images. You can drag in attachments. Not everything

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:11.440
works. Like I don't know if you can put a video in. But for my purposes, this was more than enough.

00:16:12.640 --> 00:16:20.640
So hopefully I've given you a couple of ideas of how you might try Quoto in a low stakes

00:16:20.640 --> 00:16:28.159
environment for your own kind of note taking. Of course, you can start with building a really

00:16:28.159 --> 00:16:36.719
pretty website for everyone to see. I think that's a little high stakes. So you'll find templates and

00:16:36.719 --> 00:16:42.799
more at the GitHub link on screen. And you can kind of find me on most of the socials

00:16:43.679 --> 00:16:49.520
on that handle in the middle. So I hope you will consider Quoto for your knowledge management.

00:16:49.520 --> 00:16:50.719
Thank you.

00:16:57.679 --> 00:17:04.160
Thank you, Cynthia. That was an amazing talk. I really appreciate your use of TGI ref in the

00:17:04.160 --> 00:17:12.160
interactive one. I love that package. So the most upvoted, that's supposed to be a question,

00:17:12.160 --> 00:17:17.920
but it's not a question, says are you sure you are in web dev? Wow, this was fantastic. Really cool.

00:17:18.719 --> 00:17:24.880
Oh, thank you. This is made in, so I have to admit these slides were made in Keynote.

00:17:25.439 --> 00:17:30.400
I do use Quoto slides for pretty much all my research talks. But like for this,

00:17:31.359 --> 00:17:38.800
Keynote helped bridge those like web dev gaps where I don't know how to customize reveal.js enough.

00:17:39.920 --> 00:17:46.079
That was great. So this is a question. Where do you host your Quoto websites? Quoto pub,

00:17:46.800 --> 00:17:51.280
GitHub pages, other? Yeah. So this one's an interesting

00:17:52.880 --> 00:18:01.439
problem in that I mostly have this just locally. If you want to host it, you need some sort of

00:18:01.439 --> 00:18:05.760
authentication. And so this is why I think it's a good solution for like a one person thing.

00:18:07.520 --> 00:18:13.839
I think there's like a lot of solutions out there. I currently just use the static encryptor. So

00:18:14.800 --> 00:18:22.160
I have my PhD log like hosted on Netlify attached to my website on like a special subdomain.

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:28.719
But I had to encrypt everything. Before that, I think you can implement some sort of like

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:33.520
more complicated authentication process. But again, I don't know anything about that.

00:18:34.640 --> 00:18:39.839
Okay. So this is a nice talk. What would you suggest to efficiently move notes from

00:18:39.839 --> 00:18:45.520
other apps to Quoto? Would you access the same Quoto notes across different devices like laptops

00:18:45.520 --> 00:18:52.640
and mobile phones? So I do most of my capture just like in Apple Notes, and then I like will

00:18:52.640 --> 00:19:01.280
copy them across when needed. I also have a Alfred shortcut that opens up these Quoto projects. So

00:19:01.359 --> 00:19:09.839
when I'm on my laptop, I can kind of quickly access these like my kind of repository of notes.

00:19:09.839 --> 00:19:15.920
And so I think this is kind of a personal question of like what works for you. I also just take

00:19:15.920 --> 00:19:20.800
photos of notes that I write on paper and chuck them in. So yeah, I think it's a kind of personal

00:19:20.800 --> 00:19:27.359
process. I think we have time for one more question. What do you think is the most underrated

00:19:27.359 --> 00:19:40.160
Quoto feature? I have to say the extensibility and modularity of Quoto. Like it kind of underpins

00:19:40.160 --> 00:19:45.680
everything and you see the cool things that people make. But the more you learn about how Quoto works,

00:19:45.680 --> 00:19:49.839
the more you're like, everything you see, you're like, oh, you could do another thing that's kind

00:19:49.839 --> 00:19:57.520
of similar or like an extension. And the community around Quoto who are developing like JavaScript

00:19:57.520 --> 00:20:04.319
extensions and stuff that bring this functionality in, I think that's like underrecognized and maybe

00:20:04.319 --> 00:20:10.800
like underappreciated. So yeah, I have to kind of shout out to all the people who are making really

00:20:10.800 --> 00:20:16.000
awesome Quoto extensions. Thank you again, Cynthia. Appreciate it. Thanks again to all of our

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:17.680
speakers today.

